{"title_page": "COVID-19 pandemic in Zimbabwe", "text_new": "{{short description|Ongoing COVID-19 viral pandemic in Zimbabwe}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = COVID-19 pandemic in Zimbabwe\n| map1            = \n| legend1         = \n| map2            = \n| legend2         = \n| map3            = \n| legend3         = \n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = [[Zimbabwe]]\n| first_case      = [[Victoria Falls, Zimbabwe|Victoria Falls]]\n| arrival_date    = 20 March 2020<br>({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=3|day1=20|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}})\n| origin          = \n| recovery_cases  = 5 <small>(as of 2 May)</small>\n| deaths          = 4 <small>(as of 2 May)</small>\n| confirmed_cases = 34 <small>(as of 2 May)</small><ref>{{Cite web |title=COVID-19 Update: As at 01 May, Zimbabwe had 34 confirmed cases, including five (5) recoveries and four(4) deaths. The 6 cases from Harare previously recorded as positive on 29 April have been confirmed negative after Quality Assurance.pic.twitter.com/Ie1cPLxmDa |url=https://twitter.com/MoHCCZim/status/1256421639165808640 |last=HealthZW |first=Ministry of |date=2020-05-01 |website=@MoHCCZim |language=en |access-date=2020-05-02}}</ref>\n| suspected_cases = \n| total_ili       = \n| website         = \n}}\nThe [[COVID-19 pandemic]] was confirmed to have reached [[Zimbabwe]] in March 2020. Some of Zimbabwe's provinces, especially [[Manicaland]], [[Masvingo]] and [[Mashonaland East]], also struggled with a [[malaria]] outbreak at the same time. Though malaria is treatable, the healthcare system faces drug shortages and increase strain with the spread of [[COVID-19]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/global-development/2020/apr/21/zimbabwe-faces-malaria-outbreak-as-it-locks-down-to-counter-coronavirus |title=Zimbabwe faces malaria outbreak as it locks down to counter coronavirus |date=April 21, 2020 |work=The Guardian}}</ref>\n\n__TOC__\n\n== Background ==\nOn 12 January 2020, the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) confirmed that a [[novel coronavirus]] was the cause of a respiratory illness in a cluster of people in Wuhan City, Hubei Province, China, which was reported to the WHO on 31 December 2019.<ref name=Elsevier>{{cite web |url=https://www.elsevier.com/connect/coronavirus-information-center |title=Novel Coronavirus Information Center |last=Elsevier |date= |website=Elsevier Connect|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200130171622/https://www.elsevier.com/connect/coronavirus-information-center|archive-date=30 January 2020|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=Reynolds4March2020>{{Cite news |last=Reynolds |first=Matt |url=https://www.wired.co.uk/article/china-coronavirus |title=What is coronavirus and how close is it to becoming a pandemic? |date=4 March 2020 |work=Wired UK|access-date=5 March 2020 |issn=1357-0978|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305104806/https://www.wired.co.uk/article/china-coronavirus|archive-date=5 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Case fatality rate|case fatality ratio]] for COVID-19 has been much lower than [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome|SARS of 2003]],<ref name=Imperial13March2020>{{cite web |url= https://www.imperial.ac.uk/news/196137/crunching-numbers-coronavirus/ |title=Crunching the numbers for coronavirus |website=Imperial News|access-date=15 March 2020|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200319084913/https://www.imperial.ac.uk/news/196137/crunching-numbers-coronavirus/|archive-date=19 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=Gov.ukHCIDDef>{{cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/guidance/high-consequence-infectious-diseases-hcid |title=High consequence infectious diseases (HCID); Guidance and information about high consequence infectious diseases and their management in England |last= |first= |date= |website=GOV.UK |language=en|url-status=live|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200303051938/https://www.gov.uk/guidance/high-consequence-infectious-diseases-hcid|archive-date=3 March 2020|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref> but the [[Transmission (medicine)|transmission]] has been significantly greater, with a significant total death toll.<ref name=WFSA>{{cite web |url= https://www.wfsahq.org/resources/coronavirus |title=World Federation Of Societies of Anaesthesiologists \u2013 Coronavirus |last= |first= |date= |website=www.wfsahq.org|url-status=live|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200312233527/https://www.wfsahq.org/resources/coronavirus|archive-date=12 March 2020|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=Imperial13March2020/>\n\n==Timeline==\n\n=== March 2020 ===\nOn 21 March Zimbabwe reported its first [[COVID-19]] case: a male resident of [[Victoria Falls]] who traveled back from the UK via South Africa on 15 March.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/live/2020/mar/20/coronavirus-live-updates-outbreak-deaths-italy-uk-us-australia-europe-vaccine-china-global-economy-toll-latest-update-news?page=with%3Ablock-5e7521628f08a08573fbea4b |title=Coronavirus live updates: global cases top quarter of a million, as Italy sees biggest daily rise in deaths |last=Marsh |first=Kevin Rawlinson (now); Sarah |last2=Quinn |first2=Ben |date=2020-03-20 |website=The Guardian |language=en-GB |access-date=2020-03-20 |last3=Perraudin |first3=Frances |last4=Farrer (earlier) |first4=Martin |last5=Greenfield |first5=Patrick |last6=Cowie |first6=Sam |last7=Wintour |first7=Patrick |last8=Wintour |first8=Patrick |last9=Willsher |first9=Kim}}</ref> No deaths have been reported initially as erroneously indicated in some sources since the patient continues with self-isolation at home and showing signs of recovery.<ref>{{cite web |title=BREAKING NEWS: Zimbabwe Confirms Its First Case Of Coronavirus\u2026 More Results Pending |url=https://iharare.com/zimbabwe-confirms-first-case-of-coronavirus-2/ |website=iharare.com |date=20 March 2020 |accessdate=21 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nTwo more cases in the country were confirmed on 21 March, both cases were in [[Harare]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bulawayo24.com/index-id-news-sc-national-byo-181674.html|title=BREAKING: Two new coronavirus cases confirmed in Harare|website=Bulawayo24 News|access-date=2020-03-21}}</ref> On the 23 March, it was confirmed that noted Zimbabwean journalist [[Zororo Makamba]] was the first person in the country to pass away from the virus.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/journalist-zororo-makamba-becomes-zimbabwes-first-covid-19-death-20200323|title=Journalist Zororo Makamba becomes Zimbabwe's first Covid-19 death|last=Maphanga|first=Canny|date=2020-03-23|website=News24|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timeslive.co.za/news/africa/2020-03-23-journalist-is-first-person-in-zimbabwe-to-die-from-covid-19/|title=Journalist is first person in Zimbabwe to die from Covid-19|website=TimesLIVE|language=en-ZA|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.iol.co.za/news/africa/media-personality-zororo-makamba-becomes-first-zimbabwe-coronavirus-fatality-45410008|title=Media personality Zororo Makamba becomes first Zimbabwe coronavirus fatality|last=Daniels|first=Lou-Anne|date=23 March 2020|website=www.iol.co.za|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref>\n\n=== April 2020 ===\nAfter Zororo's death, two more people have died taking the number of deaths to three.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/MoHCCZim/status/1247956570341810178|title=COVID-19 Update: As at 8 April Zimbabwe had 11 confirmed cases, including three (3) deaths.pic.twitter.com/pNuyCrNBDM|last=HealthZW|first=Ministry of|date=2020-04-08|website=@MoHCCZim|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> Due to a shortage of protective medical equipment Zimbabwean doctors filed a lawsuit against the government so that they are adequately protected when treating infected patients.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.news24.com/Africa/News/coronavirus-zimbabwe-doctors-sue-over-dire-shortage-of-protective-gear-20200407|title=Coronavirus: Zimbabwe doctors sue over 'dire shortage' of protective gear|date=2020-04-07|website=News24|language=en|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> On Monday 13 April, 3 more cases were reported resulting in the number of cases in the country totaling 17.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.zimeye.net/2020/04/13/just-in-zimbabwes-coronavirus-positive-cases-rise-to-17/|title=Just In- Zimbabwe's Coronavirus Positive Cases Rise To 17 {{!}} ZimEye|last=___|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref>\n\n==Prevention measures and effects==\nBefore there were any confirmed cases in the country, President [[Emmerson Mnangagwa]] had declared a national emergency, putting in place travel restrictions and banning large gatherings.<ref>{{cite news|accessdate=2020-03-17|title=Zimbabwe, Namibia Declare National Emergencies Over Virus|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-03-17/zimbabwe-namibia-declare-national-emergencies-over-coronavirus|newspaper=Bloomberg|date=17 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|accessdate=2020-03-17|title=Zimbabwe's President declares COVID-19 a national disaster|url=http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2020-03/17/c_138888708.htm|newspaper=Xinhua|date=17 March 2020}}</ref> The country's defence minister, [[Oppah Muchinguri]] caused controversy by stating the corona virus could be a divine punishment on Western nations for imposing sanctions on Zimbabwe.<ref>{{cite news|accessdate=2020-03-17|title=Zimbabwe, Namibia Declare National Emergencies Over Virus|url=https://gulfnews.com/world/africa/zimbabwe-minister-coronavirus-gods-punishment-for-west-1.70401945|newspaper=GulfNews|date=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 23, President [[Emmerson Mnangagwa|Mnangagwa]] announced additional measures: 1) closure of Zimbabwe's borders to all non-essential travel, except for returning residents and cargo; 2) closure of bars, nightclubs, movie houses, swimming pools, and sporting activities; 3) restriction of all public gatherings to fewer than 50 people; and 4) restriction of hospital visits to no more than one per day.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Chirisa|first1=Sharon|url=https://iharare.com/coronavirus-zim-update/|title=Coronavirus Zim Update: Ministry Of Health Statement|date=24 March 2020|work=iHarare|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Chingono|first1=Nyasha|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/23/africa/zimbabwe-broadcaster-dies-coronavirus/|title=Prominent 30-year-old Zimbabwe broadcaster dies of coronavirus|date=24 March 2020|work=CNN|accessdate=24 March 2020|last2=Busari|first2=Stephanie}}</ref> On March 27 the government announced that the country would go into a nationwide [[lockdown|lock down]] for 21 days from the 30 March on wards.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.iol.co.za/news/africa/zimbabwe-to-go-on-total-lockdown-from-monday-to-combat-coronavirus-45684111|title=Zimbabwe to go on total lockdown from Monday to combat coronavirus|website=www.iol.co.za|language=en|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref> The Victoria falls viewing sites  have also been closed as part of Zimbabwe and Zambia lock down measures.<ref name=\"Zimbabwe\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/topics/crr7mlg0rpvt/zimbabwe|title=Zimbabwe|website=BBC News|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref> Some of the restrictions of the 21-Day Lock down have been reversed; supermarkets are now allowed to sell alcohol once again.<ref name=\"Zimbabwe\"/> On 18 April the Republic of Zimbabwe celebrate its 40th independence day under lock down for the first time in the country's history.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aa.com.tr/en/africa/zimbabwe-celebrates-40th-independence-under-lockdown/1810167|title=Zimbabwe celebrates 40th independence under lockdown|website=www.aa.com.tr|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref> Amid the lock down a total of 201 malaria outbreaks were reported, 90 were controlled resulting in 131 people dying.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aa.com.tr/en/africa/zimbabwe-131-die-from-malaria-amid-covid-19-pandemic/1810170|title=Zimbabwe: 131 die from malaria amid COVID-19 pandemic|website=www.aa.com.tr|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{COVID-19}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Zimbabwe| ]]\n[[Category:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic by country|Zimbabwe]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Africa|Zimbabwe]]\n[[Category:2020 in Zimbabwe]]\n[[Category:Medical outbreaks in Zimbabwe]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Ongoing COVID-19 viral pandemic in Zimbabwe}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Zimbabwe\n| map1            = \n| legend1         = \n| map2            = \n| legend2         = \n| map3            = \n| legend3         = \n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = [[Zimbabwe]]\n| first_case      = [[Victoria Falls, Zimbabwe|Victoria Falls]]\n| arrival_date    = 20 March 2020<br>({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=3|day1=20|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}})\n| origin          = \n| recovery_cases  = 5 <small>(as of 2 May)</small>\n\n| deaths          = 4 <small>(as of 2 May)</small>\n\n| confirmed_cases = 34 <small>(as of 2 May)</small><ref>{{Cite web |title=COVID-19 Update: As at 01 May, Zimbabwe had 34 confirmed cases, including five (5) recoveries and four(4) deaths. The 6 cases from Harare previously recorded as positive on 29 April have been confirmed negative after Quality Assurance.pic.twitter.com/Ie1cPLxmDa |url=https://twitter.com/MoHCCZim/status/1256421639165808640 |last=HealthZW |first=Ministry of |date=2020-05-01 |website=@MoHCCZim |language=en |access-date=2020-05-02}}</ref>\n| suspected_cases = \n| total_ili       = \n| website         = \n}}\nThe [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] was confirmed t